Jerome Powell, the US economy's compass
description: Under attack from Trump, Jerome Powell, the Federal Reserve head, has held firm to preserve the US central bank's independence. Facing recession threats, he could announce an interest rate cut on the week of September 15, a move that Donald Trump has demanded for months.

headline: Spain cancels €700 million Israeli arms deal
description: The decision follows Prime Minister Pedro Sanchez's pledge to enshrine in law a ban on arms trade with Israel over its offensive in Gaza. On Monday, he also urged Israel's exclusion from international sport.

headline: Qatar owns 20% of property on Paris' Champs-Elysées
description: By reviewing land registry records, Le Monde determined that one-fifth of the facades on Paris's prestigious avenue are owned by the small Gulf monarchy.

headline: The Paris district where Parisians are priced out
description: In 50 years, the 8th arrondissement of the French capital, home to the Champs-Elysées and the 'Golden Triangle,' has lost nearly half its population. The mass acquisition of real estate by ultra-wealthy foreigners has driven locals out.

headline: Why French politics can't cope without an absolute majority
description: While most European countries have learned to manage their fragmented parliaments, France has failed to adapt. The 'fait majoritaire,' the political dominance of a president backed by a parliamentary majority, has so deeply shaped politics since 1962 that lawmakers have been unable to envision governments built on a base of negotiation and compromise.

headline: Undercover but never unmasked: The untold story of a KGB spy in France
description: Following archival research and interviews with witnesses, Le Monde pieced together the completely unknown story of 'Lydia Tows,' a Russian agent who died in Paris in 1999. Working in tandem with a French police officer, she carried out a decades-long infiltration mission with devastating consequences.
